**76th World Health Assembly - Daily Report: 27 May 2023.** The first global strategy for preventing and controlling infections – the World Health Assembly today agreed on the first-ever global strategy for preventing and controlling infections (IPC), which builds on nearly two decades of WHO-led and partner efforts. The strategy provides member states with strategic guidance to significantly reduce the ongoing risk of healthcare-associated infections (HAIs), including those exhibiting antimicrobial resistance. HAIs are among the most frequent adverse events occurring within the context of healthcare delivery. The COVID-19 pandemic and recent outbreaks of diseases such as Ebola virus, the Middle East respiratory syndrome, and Sudan virus have clearly revealed existing gaps in IPC programs in all countries.

The strategy sets a clear direction: By 2030, everyone who receives or provides healthcare is safe from infection. Its three main goals are: Preventing infections in healthcare; taking action to ensure IPC plans are in place and implemented; and coordinating IPC activities with other areas and sectors. The strategy focuses on any environment where healthcare is delivered, within the health system; it is based on the principle of safe and clean care as a fundamental part of the right to health, which is driven by equity, and which should ensure accountability and sustainability. The global IPC strategy will be complemented by, and used in conjunction with, an international implementation plan associated with a monitoring system, which will be developed in 2023-2024.

**Related Document EB 152/9 – Draft global strategy on preventing and controlling infections, Executive Summary Report of the Director-General WHO Work on preventing and controlling infections.** A historic resolution paves the way for strengthening rehabilitation in health systems today. The World Health Assembly has adopted a key resolution on strengthening rehabilitation in health systems. Rehabilitation services play a vital role in ensuring the enjoyment of human rights, including the highest attainable standard of physical and mental health. It also promotes sexual and reproductive health and recognizes the right to work and the right to education. This important resolution aims to address challenges in rehabilitation such as the need to:

*   Increase awareness of rehabilitation during the setting of health priorities and research agendas, resource allocation, promote collaboration and facilitate technology transfer;
*   Ensure countries have sufficient capacity to cope with sudden increases in rehabilitation needs, including assistive technology, due to health emergencies;
*   Ensure that people in vulnerable and hazardous environments receive affordable, quality, and appropriate rehabilitation, including assistive technology;
*   Avoid the high out-of-pocket costs for people to access rehabilitation services and assistive technology, which can lead to financial hardship; and
*   Address the current inadequate level of rehabilitation workforce to serve the needs of people.

The resolution lists a range of actions to be taken by the WHO Secretariat, such as:

*   Publishing a baseline report by the end of 2026 with information on the capacity of member states to respond to rehabilitation needs;
*   Developing standards and indicators for the delivery of quality rehabilitation services by 2030;
*   Ensuring adequate resources are targeted within WHO to support member states in implementing technical guidance and resources; and
*   Assisting member states in integrating rehabilitation and assistive technology into their emergency preparedness and response plans.

The WHO Secretariat will report on progress in the implementation of this resolution to the Health Assembly in 2026, 2028, and 2030.
